<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="ai-accessibility-automation-2026">
  <metadata>
    <tier>geek</tier>
    <group>ux</group>
    <domain>accessibility-specialist</domain>
    <summary>Continuous accessibility automation: axe scans, AI ranks violations, code fixes suggested, VPAT 2.5 drafts generated, captions/alt-text automated.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>accessibility</tag>
      <tag>wcag</tag>
      <tag>ada-compliance</tag>
      <tag>automation</tag>
      <tag>vpat</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>advanced</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-25</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>AI Accessibility Automation 2026</title>
    <summary>Full continuous accessibility automation pipeline for products with frequent deployments: axe-playwright scans every deploy, AI ranks and de-duplicates violations, code fixes are suggested per issue, VPAT 2.5 drafts are generated from scan summaries, and caption/alt-text pipelines run on every media upload. All AI outputs are gated by a human accessibility lead before entering the developer backlog.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>94.8% of homepages still fail WCAG 2 (WebAIM 2026). Manual audits ($5k–$20k each) happen at most twice a year; AI-assisted continuous monitoring costs $100–$2,000/month and catches regressions before production. ADA Title II compliance (effective April 2026 for state/local government) requires documented conformance — AI VPAT drafting converts hours of work to seconds.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Establishing continuous accessibility monitoring in a CI/CD pipeline for a product with frequent deployments</item>
        <item>Generating ADA Title II compliance documentation (effective 2026) for public-sector or higher-education digital products</item>
        <item>Scaling accessibility remediation across a large codebase where manual triaging is cost-prohibitive</item>
        <item>Producing AI-assisted VPAT drafts for enterprise procurement processes</item>
        <item>Automating captioning and audio description pipelines for video-heavy content operations</item>
        <item>Setting up regression prevention so new code does not reintroduce fixed violations</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>The team has no existing accessibility baseline — start with a manual audit first to understand the real state</item>
        <item>Product is in pre-MVP prototyping — defer automation until the UI stabilizes</item>
        <item>AI automation is being proposed as a replacement for user testing with people who use assistive technology</item>
        <item>The team plans to deploy AI overlay widgets as the compliance strategy (overlays do not satisfy ADA Title II)</item>
        <item>Budget is the only driver — automation tools cost $100–$2,000/month; weigh against compliance risk</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="limitations">
      <p>Even AI-enhanced scanning covers only 60–70% of WCAG success criteria; 30–40% requires human judgment.</p>
      <p>Cognitive accessibility (WCAG 2.2 new SCs: 3.3.7, 3.3.8) is almost entirely outside current AI detection.</p>
      <p>AI-suggested code fixes for complex ARIA patterns are frequently wrong — require human validation.</p>
      <p>VPAT drafts require legal/compliance review before submission; AI cannot assess organizational conformance claims.</p>
      <p>Video auto-captions at AI-only accuracy (80–90%) violate ADA Title II requirements — always pair with human review.</p>
      <p>AI prioritization reflects traffic-based impact estimates, not the actual severity for individual users with disabilities.</p>
      <p>The ADA Title II deadline for state/local government compliance was April 2026 — late adopters face immediate legal risk.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="ai-vs-traditional-comparison">
      <list>
        <item>Issue detection: traditional 30–50% coverage; AI-enhanced 60–70% with context</item>
        <item>False positives: traditional 30–40%; AI-reduced 10–15%</item>
        <item>Code remediation: traditional manual; AI suggests fixes with code snippets</item>
        <item>VPAT creation: traditional hours; AI generates draft in seconds</item>
        <item>Issue prioritization: traditional manual triage; AI ranks by user impact and traffic</item>
        <item>Alt text generation: traditional manual writing; AI suggests from image content</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="enterprise-platforms">
      <list>
        <item>Deque axe DevTools Pro: SaaS. AI issue extraction + fix suggestions; ADA Title II reporting. Yes — CLI + API agent-friendly.</item>
        <item>Evinced: SaaS. AI-powered continuous scanning; REST API for issue data. Yes — CI/CD integration agent-friendly.</item>
        <item>AudioEye: SaaS. AI remediation with human oversight; not overlay-based. Partial agent-friendly.</item>
        <item>3Play Media: SaaS. ADA-compliant captions (AI + human review, 99% accuracy). Yes — REST API agent-friendly.</item>
        <item>Rev.ai: SaaS. 80–90% accuracy AI captions; needs human review step. Yes — REST API agent-friendly.</item>
        <item>Microsoft Azure Computer Vision: SaaS. Bulk alt text generation from image URLs/bytes. Yes — REST API agent-friendly.</item>
        <item>Siteimprove: SaaS. Enterprise monitoring + trend analysis; API for issue data. Yes — REST API agent-friendly.</item>
        <item>Level Access: SaaS. Ask Level AI for WCAG Q&amp;A; no programmatic scan API. Partial — chatbot only.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="ada-title-ii-context">
      <rule>
        <statement>For state/local government or higher-education digital products, document WCAG 2.2 AA conformance with a VPAT 2.5 — AI drafting compresses this from hours to seconds but requires human legal review before external use.</statement>
        <rationale>The ADA Title II final rule (effective April 2026) requires WCAG 2.2 AA compliance for state/local government digital products. Late adopters face immediate legal risk. VPAT drafts are legally significant documents.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="video-accessibility">
      <list>
        <item>3Play Media: AI transcription + human review (99% accuracy); REST API</item>
        <item>Rev.ai: automated captions 80–90% accuracy; needs human review</item>
        <item>Otter.ai: real-time transcription</item>
        <item>YouTube Auto-Captions: free but always needs manual review</item>
        <item>AI audio descriptions: YouDescribe (crowdsourced + AI), AI.Film (automated scenes), Descriptive Video Works (AI draft + human polish)</item>
        <item>Live captioning: Google Live Captions, Microsoft Teams, Zoom (with speaker ID)</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="5-stage-workflow">
      <list>
        <item>1. AI-Powered Automated Scan: axe-playwright + WAVE + Lighthouse; baseline report with prioritized issues; false positives filtered</item>
        <item>2. AI Issue Extraction: developer-friendly context; code snippets auto-extracted; visual annotations on screenshots; WCAG criterion reference</item>
        <item>3. AI Fix Suggestions: code recommendations ranked by impact; multiple approaches; best practice guidance</item>
        <item>4. Human Review: validation of AI suggestions; edge case identification; context-specific decisions; human-in-loop checkpoint before developer tickets</item>
        <item>5. Continuous AI Monitoring: regression prevention on every deploy; new page scanning; trend analysis and reporting</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="human-vs-ai-responsibilities">
      <list>
        <item>AI handles: repetitive scanning, code extraction, report formatting, WCAG Q&amp;A chatbot, draft alt text, priority ranking by traffic, regression testing automation</item>
        <item>Humans handle: empathy in content decisions, meaningful alt text judgment, user testing validation, strategic fix decisions, edge cases, final AI output review, accessibility culture</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="baseline-and-regression-rules">
      <rule>
        <statement>Set a WCAG 2.2 AA baseline on the current codebase before enabling CI gates — gate on regressions, not the full backlog.</statement>
        <rationale>Gating on the full existing backlog blocks all deploys immediately. Gating on regressions prevents new violations while allowing the team to fix the backlog incrementally.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Separate the automated backlog (AI-found) from the manual backlog (human-found) without merging unless source is tagged.</statement>
        <rationale>Mixing sources obscures coverage gaps. An all-green automated backlog may still have significant undetected manual issues.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Track false positive rate monthly — if AI filter marks real issues as false positives, retune the filter rules.</statement>
        <rationale>AI false-positive filters are not static. As the codebase evolves, the filter rules may exclude genuine violations. Monthly review prevents drift.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>A Claude subagent (Haiku) orchestrates a multi-tool scan pipeline: axe-playwright for WCAG violations, 3Play Media API for video caption jobs, and Azure Computer Vision for bulk alt text generation. A Sonnet subagent receives the aggregated issue JSON and produces ranked remediation tickets with code fix suggestions attached. A Haiku subagent generates the VPAT draft from the scan summary and uploads it to a shared document store. All outputs are gated by a human accessibility lead before entering the developer backlog.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="recommended-subagents">
      <list>
        <item>General Claude subagent (Haiku): scan orchestration, false-positive filtering, VPAT section drafting</item>
        <item>General Claude subagent (Sonnet): code fix generation, WCAG criterion explanation, issue ticket authoring</item>
        <item>General Claude subagent (Haiku): bulk alt text generation, caption job submission, report aggregation</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="best-practices">
      <list>
        <item>Set a WCAG 2.2 AA baseline on the current codebase before enabling CI gates — gate on regressions, not the full backlog</item>
        <item>Separate the automated backlog (AI-found) from the manual backlog (human-found); never merge them without tagging the source</item>
        <item>For ADA Title II compliance: document both what passes and what does not pass; VPAT requires honest assessment, not just wins</item>
        <item>Prioritize Critical violations on high-traffic pages first; AI traffic-based ranking is a useful starting point</item>
        <item>Caption pipeline: submit to 3Play Media (or equivalent) immediately on video upload; never publish without 99%-accuracy captions</item>
        <item>Track false positive rate monthly — if AI filter is marking real issues as false positives, retune the filter rules</item>
        <item>Brief developers on WCAG intent, not just rule ID — "why" knowledge reduces recurrence of the same violation type</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="ai-agent-gotchas">
      <list>
        <item>VPAT drafts are legal documents; any AI-generated conformance claim that is inaccurate exposes the organization to legal risk — mandatory human review before any external use</item>
        <item>Axe JSON from large single-page applications can exceed 100KB — chunk by page/component before sending to LLM</item>
        <item>Agent-generated code fixes for ARIA roles are error-prone for complex widget patterns (combobox, tree, grid) — flag these for senior review</item>
        <item>Alt text agents lack brand voice and image purpose context; always provide surrounding page context in the prompt</item>
        <item>Human-in-loop checkpoint: accessibility lead must approve ranked issue list before developer tickets are created</item>
        <item>Do not auto-close issues based on AI re-scan alone — require a human to confirm the fix works with real assistive technology</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="cli-tools">
      <list>
        <item>axe-playwright: Headless WCAG scanning — most accurate OSS tool. Install: npm install @axe-core/playwright</item>
        <item>pa11y-ci: Batch URL scanning in CI pipelines. Install: npm install -g pa11y-ci</item>
        <item>lighthouse-ci: Combined perf + a11y scoring gate. Install: npm install -g @lhci/cli</item>
        <item>jest-axe: Unit-level component a11y assertions. Install: npm install jest-axe</item>
        <item>cypress-axe: E2E a11y assertions in Cypress tests. Install: npm install cypress-axe</item>
        <item>eslint-plugin-jsx-a11y: Static JSX a11y linting (catches issues at write time). Install: npm install eslint-plugin-jsx-a11y</item>
        <item>htmlhint: Validates accessible HTML structure. Install: npm install htmlhint</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="antipatterns">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Publishing AI-generated VPAT sections externally without human legal/compliance review</description>
        <reason>VPAT drafts are legal documents. Any inaccurate conformance claim exposes the organization to legal risk. DRAFT watermark is mandatory on all AI-generated sections; human sign-off required before any external use.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Auto-closing issues based on AI re-scan alone without human confirmation on real assistive technology</description>
        <reason>AI scan confirms the code pattern changed, not that the fix works for actual users. A regression may exist that the scanner cannot detect. Human validation on VoiceOver, NVDA, or JAWS is required before closure.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Deploying AI overlay widgets as the ADA Title II compliance strategy</description>
        <reason>Overlays do not satisfy ADA Title II requirements. They are JavaScript patches that cannot fix semantic HTML issues, keyboard navigation, or focus management. Organizations that rely on overlays remain non-compliant.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent-generated code fixes for complex ARIA widget patterns (combobox, tree, grid) applied without senior review</description>
        <reason>ARIA widget patterns require precise role/state/property relationships. AI-generated fixes for these patterns are frequently incorrect and may introduce new accessibility failures.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Sending large SPA axe JSON (100KB+) to LLM in a single prompt</description>
        <reason>Large single-page apps generate axe reports that exceed LLM context limits. Chunk by page or component before sending; aggregate results after processing.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Starting automation without an existing accessibility baseline</description>
        <reason>Without a baseline, CI gates immediately block all deploys due to the full existing backlog. Establish a baseline first, then gate on regressions only.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="prompt-patterns">
      <p>Prompt for accessibility scan triage with ranked issue report:</p>
      <code lang="text"><![CDATA[You are an accessibility automation engineer. Given this axe-core scan report (JSON),
perform the following:
1. Remove violations where the element is aria-hidden or display:none (likely false positives)
2. Rank remaining violations: Critical (A failures affecting all users), High (AA failures),
   Medium (A failures with workarounds), Low (AAA or minor)
3. Group related violations by component type
4. For each Critical and High issue, generate a concrete code fix in [framework]
5. Output: { summary: {...}, issues: [...], fixes: {...} }
Do not invent issues not present in the scan data.]]></code>
      <p>Prompt for VPAT 2.5 draft generation:</p>
      <code lang="text"><![CDATA[Draft the following VPAT 2.5 sections based on this scan summary: [summary JSON].
For each WCAG criterion, output one of: Supports | Partially Supports | Does Not Support | Not Applicable.
Add a one-sentence note for each non-"Supports" entry explaining what fails.
Mark all entries as DRAFT — human review required before publication.]]></code>
    </section>
    <section name="ci-gate-script">
      <p>CI gate script (blocks deployment on new Critical violations):</p>
      <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[#!/usr/bin/env bash
# ci-a11y-gate.sh — fail build if new Critical a11y violations introduced
set -euo pipefail

BASELINE="${1:-a11y-baseline.json}"
CURRENT="a11y-current.json"

npx axe-cli \
  --browser chrome \
  --tags wcag2a,wcag2aa \
  --reporter json \
  "$(cat urls.txt)" > "$CURRENT"

python3 - <<'EOF'
import json, sys

baseline = json.load(open("a11y-baseline.json")) if __import__("os").path.exists("a11y-baseline.json") else {"violations": []}
current = json.load(open("a11y-current.json"))

baseline_ids = {v["id"] for v in baseline.get("violations", [])}
new_violations = [v for v in current.get("violations", []) if v["id"] not in baseline_ids and v["impact"] == "critical"]

if new_violations:
    print(f"FAIL: {len(new_violations)} new Critical a11y violations introduced:")
    for v in new_violations:
        print(f"  - {v['id']}: {v['description']}")
    sys.exit(1)
print("PASS: No new Critical a11y violations.")
EOF]]></code>
    </section>
    <see-also>
      <link href="https://webaim.org/projects/million/">WebAIM Million 2026</link>
      <link href="https://www.ada.gov/resources/web-guidance/">ADA Title II final rule</link>
      <link href="https://www.deque.com/blog/ai-accessibility-testing/">Deque AI accessibility</link>
      <link href="https://www.w3.org/TR/WCAG22/">WCAG 2.2</link>
      <link href="https://www.itic.org/policy/accessibility/vpat">VPAT 2.5 template</link>
      <link href="https://www.3playmedia.com/solutions/features/apis/">3Play Media captioning API</link>
    </see-also>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/ci-a11y-gate.sh" purpose="CI gate: runs axe-cli, diffs against baseline, fails on new Critical violations"/>
      <template path="templates/prompt-scan-triage.txt" purpose="Haiku prompt: axe JSON → filtered, ranked, grouped issue report with fixes"/>
      <template path="templates/prompt-vpat-draft.txt" purpose="Haiku prompt: scan summary → VPAT 2.5 section draft with DRAFT watermark"/>
    </templates>
  </content>
</methodology>
